===Glyph origin===
{{Han etym}}
{{liushu|p}} of an axe or halberd, almost identical to [[戊]] and similar to [[戈]].

===Etymology 1===
{{zh-ref|Smith (2011)}} proposes that {{och-l|戌}}, graphically depicting an ax or halberd, is a nominal derivative of the verb {{och-l|滅}} "to annihilate" "by the multivalent prefix *s- (‘annihilate’ > ‘annihilator’ and thus ‘axe’)", and it was used to name the late, broad waxing crescent moon.

Association with the dog was possibly arbitrary, just as how [[辰]] was associated arbitrarily with the dragon (see {{zh-ref|Ferlus, 2013}}).

